posts.name: Anshu Adiga
posts.cooked: We do have belts to guide the coral, but the funnel closure helps secure it more when the robot moves quickly in and out of the station area. This feature was especially useful in V2 when we needed to store coral passively in the funnel. We aimed for rapid acceleration (from stow to L4) and chose 4 motors over 6 due to the negligible 20 ms difference. We maximized weight extraction from various components, including the elevator, end effector, funnel, and drive chassis.

posts.name: Mactar Gueye
posts.cooked: I have really loved the 190 climber since seeing it at the week zero event and have tried to replicate it before. Taking a look at it could you possibly explain how it deploys I’d assume it has to do with the blue circle in this image. I was also wondering what the yellow circle does is it a pulley for the rope? Finally I was wondering what your rope path looked like and how the grappling hook is attached to the entire assembly.

posts.name: Alex Fenwick
posts.cooked: We received questions about our setup. #1 Initially we didn’t have flip-up motion and had difficulty achieving the desired effect, especially at lower settings. The star wheel helped grip the coral and flip it onto L4. #2 Building on feedback from Anshu, we added a clapping funnel to both manipulate the coral and assist in the climbing process. The digital object format (DOF) was essential for positioning the funnel, so we incorporated it. #6 Our shop features advanced equipment including a Haas VF4SS Mill, Bridgeport Mill, 2 lathes, ShopSabre Router, Laser cutter, powder cutting booth, and additional tools like bambus and Markforged components. #7 We started the season aiming to win Week 1 competition with V1, while V2 focused on high-level play using our precision machining skills. Due to time constraints, V2 ended up adopting a design closer to V1. #8 Shush face emoji.

posts.name: Peter Cooper Jr.
posts.cooked: The name “Gompei and the HERD” originated during the FIRST team naming era at WPI & Mass. Academy in the mid-1990s. The team nickname reflected its mascot, Gompei, a goat named after its former mascot-keeper, Col. Ken Stafford. The team members were also named Gompei, creating the playful nickname “Gompei and the H.E.R.D.”, with “HERD” serving as an acronym with no specific meaning, adding humor to the branding.

posts.name: Grant Watson
posts.cooked: The deployment process requires understanding the role of the blue circle, though it isn't essential for activating the arm. A 40lb pulling gas spring maintains the downward tension efficiently. To prevent the grappling hook from retracting too soon, a pulley redirects the string, ensuring it remains taut. The system relies on standoffs, plates, and precise mechanisms for stability. Testing with magnets failed due to the intense shock during deployment. The mechanism uses a 5-bar linkage with a spring to adjust string tension effectively. Magnetic blocks ensure the string remains secure, preventing tangling. Buttons were installed internally to enhance safety and performance.

posts.name: Akhil Rao Narahari
posts.cooked: How much weight did you have to save for the algae intake and end effector? What methods did you use to understand how much weight to pull from each subsystem without losing any physical integrity? Also, how many revisions did it take to get your algae functionality to a good spot and what was the toughest challenge during that process?

posts.name: Alex Fenwick
posts.cooked:
Overall, for the Algae Claw and OTB intake, we needed to add approximately 10-15 pounds of weight. After completing the V1 build and weighing it, we gained insights into how much weight needed to be cut based on our desired additions. Fortunately, we managed to reduce the weight significantly from the funnel and elevator gearbox, along with the elevator carriage, without compromising strength (approximately 3 pounds from the elevator motors alone). Additionally, we upgraded most components to 3/8-inch Thunder Hex, saving further weight.

Several risks emerged during the build, primarily related to the elevator and drive tubes. Initially, we only lightened the front and back drive rails, but after assembling the robot, we decided to partially lighten the side rails due to the need for more weight. Unfortunately, this caused the climber side drive rail to bend slightly during the Battle Cry test phase.

To enhance the Algae Claw's performance, we adjusted its torque requirements, increasing it from two X44s to an X60 for better reliability. We also modified the claw's geometry, deepening the "C" shape. Various experiments included trying different wheels, grip tapes, and stall voltages. An additional modification involved adding a small roller between the wheels, using a 1.25-inch tube with grip tape.

During testing, we encountered frequent belt engagement issues with algae. To solve this, we added several 3D-printed idlers around the pulleys, resulting in around 10-15 iterations throughout the week leading up to the WPI event, including nearly three full swaps during the event itself.

The Lightened Side Rail and Claw Tensioner modifications were critical to addressing structural weaknesses. Despite the complexities, our iterative process ultimately yielded a functional and improved design.
